{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a96e0624-46b1-49fa-aa47-1de693811ca9","content":"I can help guide you through analyzing your crash dump. The `dump-collect` skill I have available is only for **collecting** dumps, not analyzing them — so let me give you direct guidance instead.\n\n## Analyzing a .NET crash dump\n\nHere are the main tools you can use:\n\n**1. `dotnet-dump analyze` (cross-platform, easiest)**\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\ndotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp\n```\nUseful commands inside the REPL:\n- `clrstack` — managed call stack of the current thread\n- `clrthreads` — list all managed threads\n- `pe` — print the last exception\n- `dumpheap -stat` — heap overview\n- `dso` — dump stack objects\n\n**2. `lldb` with SOS (Linux/macOS)**\n```bash\ndotnet-sos install\nlldb --core your-file.dmp\n```\nThen: `sos clrstack`, `sos pe`, etc.\n\n**3. WinDbg (Windows)**\nOpen the dump, load SOS with `.loadby sos coreclr`, then use `!clrstack`, `!pe`, `!threads`.\n\n---\n\n**Quick triage steps:**\n1. Run `pe` (print exception) to see if an unhandled exception caused the crash.\n2. Run `clrthreads` to find the faulting thread.\n3. Run `clrstack` on that thread to get the call stack.\n\nWould you like me to help you run `dotnet-dump analyze` on your file right now? If so, share the path to your `.dmp` file.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"93aad617-47f3-4d8a-a013-ad1939f02575","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a \"dump-collect\" skill, but its description explicitly says \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze.\" So I should not invoke that skill.\n\nI'll help the user directly with guidance on analyzing their dump file.","outputTokens":495,"requestId":"AC12:1910FB:14A9A51:171ACCC:6A067272"},"id":"d6a3a291-5386-4c34-804f-ebe15014e498","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01: